ce covered zero for only one species (red salamander$\backslash$nPseudotriton ruber). After adjusting for goodness-of-fit, point$\backslash$nestimates of differences in occupancy and conditional abundance still$\backslash$nremained below zero for most species. Additionally, MTR/VF reaches had$\backslash$nhigher ion concentrations, total organic carbon and specific conductance$\backslash$ncompared to reference reaches.Synthesis and applications. Our study$\backslash$nconcludes that mountaintop removal mining and valley filling (MTR/VF)$\backslash$nreduces salamander occupancy and conditional abundance. Although the$\backslash$npotential mechanisms responsible for reduction are numerous, our$\backslash$nfindings suggest a change in the current regulatory framework is needed$\backslash$nto offset the impacts of MTR/VF on stream ecosystems and biota.$\backslash$nReclamation techniques that enhance conditions for vegetative succession$\backslash$nwithin catchments may improve habitat on reclaimed surface mines.$\backslash$nOur study concludes that mountaintop removal mining and valley filling$\backslash$n(MTR/VF) reduces salamander occupancy and conditional abundance.$\backslash$nAlthough the potential mechanisms responsible for reduction are$\backslash$nnumerous, our findings suggest a change in the current regulatory$\backslash$nframework is needed to offset the impacts of MTR/VF on stream ecosystems$\backslash$nand biota. Reclamation techniques that enhance conditions for vegetative$\backslash$nsuccession within catchments may improve habitat on reclaimed surface$\backslash$nmines.},
